{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "If available, researchers can use pre-existing dictionaries (ready-made dictionaries [RMDs]), such as the widely used Linguistic Inquiry and Word Count (LIWC) dictionary (Pennebaker et al., 2015).",
    "An alternative is to create a custom-made dictionary (CMD) suited for the particular coding scheme and dataset at hand (Bonikowski & Gidron, 2016; Macanovic, 2022; Nelson et al., 2021; Spörlein & Schlueter, 2021).",
    "We present a straightforward approach that uses manually coded data to automatically generate dictionaries using the concept of word keyness from computational linguistics (Gabrielatos, 2018).",
    "To illustrate this procedure, consider the following example: If, in our sample of 1,000 manually coded texts, we have coded 100 texts for the emotion category of \"joy,\" we denote these 100 texts as the \"target group\" and the remaining 900 texts as the \"reference group\".",
    "For instance, if the word \"happy\" occurs 20 times in the target group, but only 10 times in the reference group, we use a word keyness measure to assess the extent of the difference in word occurrence between the groups."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "If available, researchers can use pre-existing dictionaries (ready-made dictionaries [RMDs]), such as the widely used Linguistic Inquiry and Word Count (LIWC) dictionary (Pennebaker et al., 2015).",
    "An alternative is to create a custom-made dictionary (CMD) suited for the particular coding scheme and dataset at hand (Bonikowski & Gidron, 2016; Macanovic, 2022; Nelson et al., 2021; Spörlein & Schlueter, 2021).",
    "We present a straightforward approach that uses manually coded data to automatically generate dictionaries using the concept of word keyness from computational linguistics (Gabrielatos, 2018)."
